## Improved app.js

```js
const express = require('express');
const request = require('./utils/request');
const logger = require('./utils/logger');
const constants = require('./utils/constants');

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());

app.all('/:url', async (req, res) => {
  const { url } = req.params;

  if (!constants.ALLOWED_METHODS.includes(req.method)) {
    return res.status(405).send('Method not allowed');
  }

  try {
    const data = await request(url, {
      method: req.method,
      data: req.body,
      headers: req.headers,
    });
    return res.send(data);
  } catch (error) {
    logger.error(error);
    return res.status(500).send('Internal server error');
  }
});

app.listen(process.env.PORT || 3000, () => {
  logger.info(`Proxy listening on port ${process.env.PORT || 3000}`);
});
```

## Explanations

**app.js**

The `app.js` file is the main entry point of the proxy. It uses the `express` framework to create an Express application. The application has a single route, which is a wildcard route that proxies requests to the target URL.

The `request` module is used to make HTTP requests to the target URL. The `logger` module is used to log errors and other information. The `constants` module contains the list of allowed HTTP methods.

The `app.listen()` method is used to start the Express application. The application listens on the port specified by the `PORT` environment variable, or on port 3000 if the `PORT` environment variable is not set.

**utils/request.js**

The `utils/request.js` file contains the function that is used to make HTTP requests to the target URL. The function uses the `axios` library to make the requests.

**utils/constants.js**

The `utils/constants.js` file contains the list of allowed HTTP methods. The list of allowed methods is currently empty, but it can be updated to include additional methods in the future.

**.env**

The `.env` file contains the environment variables that are used by the proxy. The `PORT` environment variable specifies the port on which the proxy should listen.

## New Files

**utils/logger.js**

The `utils/logger.js` file contains the functions that are used to log errors and other information.

```js
const pino = require('pino');

const logger = pino({
  level: 'info',
  prettyPrint: true,
});

module.exports = logger;
```

**app.test.js**

The `app.test.js` file contains the unit tests for the proxy.

```js
const request = require('supertest');
const app = require('../app');

describe('GET /', () => {
  it('should proxy the request to the target URL', async () => {
    const res = await request(app).get('/');
    expect(res.status).toBe(200);
    expect(res.text).toBe('Hello, world!');
  });

  it('should log the request', async () => {
    const logger = require('../utils/logger');
    const spy = jest.spyOn(logger, 'info');

    await request(app).get('/');

    expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
});
```